        <TextView
            android:id="@+id/textViewlessonsix6"
            android:layout_width="360dp"
            android:layout_height="600dp"
            android:text="In the event of a fire, your primary thoughts should be of the safety of you and your family. If there is any doubt about staying at home or leaving, leave immediately. It is important to have an evacuation plan in place and to practice it. This will ensure that you and your family know and understand how to get out of the house. Here’s a checklist of fire safety considerations:\n
- Have an escape plan for each room and make the bedrooms top priority. Rehearse the plan regularly as a rehearsed escape plan will help eliminate panic in an emergency situation.\n
- Once the alarm sounds, time is of the essence. Don’t stop to gather valuables or toys — just get out.\n
- Designate a window as a secondary exit. Make sure it is completely unobstructed and is easily opened by children and elderly. For second and third story windows, keep a Fire Escape Ladder stored close by.\n
- Feel closed doors for warmth before opening them and look for smoke seeping in around the door’s edges and from underneath. Open any closed door slowly and be prepared to shut it immediately if heat or smoke rush in.\n
- Have a designated outside meeting place, and make everyone aware of where it is.\n
- As soon as two people have reached the meeting place, have one person leave to call 911. The second person should stay to make sure the other family members all make it out.\n
- If someone is missing don’t go back inside. Instead, notify the fire department as soon as they arrive.\n
"
            app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf="parent"
            app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf="parent"
            app:layout_constraintTop_toBottomOf="@+id/imageViewlessonsixfourth" />

